comment:
This is a wonderful primer on the lay of the land. I wanted to provide a few notes on your civics lesson (not trying to law-splain).
@12:09 Lower courts doesn't have any derogatory or icky meaning. They are called lower courts because they are subordinate courts. Imagine it like appealing up the ranks in a company. You have the trial level (generally federal district courts), and if a party isn't satisfied with the outcome at the trial level, they appeal to the appropriate circuit court (1st Circuit, 2nd Circuit, 3rd Circuit, etc.)...It's like filing a complaint with the manager.  The appellate court has more weight than the trial court. If a party is not satisfied at the appellate court, then they can appeal to the Supreme Court (i.e., taking their complaint up the chain). An interesting thing to note is that the appellate level hears all appeals, but the Supreme Court chooses which cases it takes. So when they call them lower courts, it's not that their function is less important, they are a different rung in the process.
@12:20 The Supreme court doesn't hold trials and doesn't issue verdicts. It holds hearings, in which each side advocates their to explain why the subordinate court got the decision right or wrong, and how they encourage the Supreme Court to rule (the less glamorous aspect is that each side submits tons and tons of written briefs in support of their argument or things the Court should consider when they rule.).  The outcome is not a verdict. It is a ruling. The opinion is the explanation of the result or ruling.
@15:46 It's not "months years decades" of deliberation. At most it's a few years. The justices will decide whether to hear a case (remember they get to choose their cases), and then they will schedule it for argument. The Supreme Court term is October-June. Based on the argument date, that determines the deadlines for the interested parties to submit their written briefing. Once a case is heard, the decision will come out by the end of that term. So a ruling will be issued within that term or at least before the following October. (Historically they usually issue all decisions by June 30, but sometimes have gone into July. June 30 is not an absolute cut-off.) Occasionally, a court may decide to *rehear* a case before issuing a ruling. This actually happened with Roe v. Wade. It was first argued December 13, 1971, and when the judges couldn't reach a consensus, it was reargued October 11, 1972.  The decision wasn't released until January 1973. Brown v. Board of Education is also a famous case that was reargued. The issue may be brewing in the zeitgeist and in the subordinate courts for decades, but once it gets to SCOTUS, it takes a few years at most, usually months, not decades.
